1. Oriqin and contente of the book “On the Churoh''.

At the present date, at which only a comparatively small portion of Wyclif's works have appeared in print, it may still be doubtful to which of them the palm belongs, both in respect of form and contents3 but at least it may safely be said, that his book on the Church must be reckoned amongst his ripest and most important utteranceS. For, let us consider what a powerful impression the work by Hus bearing the same title, produced upon his contemporarie53 a work which, as Pierre d'Ailly said‚1 “by its immense abundance of proofs‚ combats the authority and plenary power of the Pope, no less than the Koran combats the Catholic faith''. And yet this celebrated book is only a meagre abridgment of Wyclif's “De Ecclesia’'. What if the contemporaries of Hus, who as assembled at Constance represented the intellectual capacity of the Europe of that day, had known the original that he had drawn upon, instead of the feeble imitation l

In order rightly to understand the origin of the treatise on the Church, we must go back to the years 1377 and 1378, during which Wyclif found himself exposed to attack from the combined forces of the hierarchy, or, as many at that time said, of the Church. The hierarchy however is not the Church: and it is the distinction between what the Church is in reality‚ and what the multitude under— stand by it,‘2 which Wyclif sets himself to expound in this work.
